  "prompt": "How do QR codes work?",
  "response": "QR codes, or Quick Response codes, are two-dimensional barcodes that can store information in a machine-readable format. Here's how they work:\n\n### Structure of QR Codes\n1. **Modules**: QR codes consist of black squares (modules) arranged in a square grid on a white background. The arrangement of these modules encodes information.\n2. **Patterns**: QR codes have specific patterns:\n   - **Positioning Markers**: Three large squares in three corners help scanners identify the code's orientation.\n   - **Timing Patterns**: Alternating black and white modules that help determine the grid's dimensions.\n   - **Version Information**: Indicates the QR code's version, which determines its size and data capacity.\n   - **Format Information**: Provides error correction level and mask pattern used.\n\n### Data Encoding\nQR codes can encode various types of data, including:\n- Numeric\n- Alphanumeric\n- Binary\n- Kanji\n\nThe data is compressed and converted into a binary string, which is then represented by the arrangement of the black and white modules.\n\n### Error Correction\nQR codes use Reed-Solomon error correction, allowing them to be read correctly even if they are partially damaged or obscured. There are four levels of error correction (L, M, Q, H) that determine how much of the code can be restored.\n\n### Scanning QR Codes\n1. **Camera/Scanner**: A QR code is scanned using a camera or a dedicated QR code scanner. Many smartphones have built-in QR code scanning capabilities in their camera apps.\n2. **Image Processing**: The scanning device detects the positioning markers to orient and read the code.\n3. **Decoding**: The scanner processes the pattern of black and white modules to convert them back into binary data, which is then translated into readable information (like a URL, text, or other data).\n4. **Action**: The decoded data can trigger various actions, such as opening a website, displaying text, or adding contact information.\n\n### Applications\nQR codes have a wide range of applications, including:\n- Marketing (linking to promotions or websites)\n- Payments (mobile payment systems)\n- Inventory management\n- Event ticketing\n- Product information (e.g., on packaging)\n\nOverall, QR codes are a versatile and efficient way to transmit information quickly and conveniently.",
